        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "[codex] Migrate Chrome companion to optional Native Messaging",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- replace the Chrome extension loopback daemon transport with an exact-extension-ID Native Messaging host\n- keep `nativeMessaging` optional and request it only from explicit Daemon enablement\n- add managed `daemonAllowed=false` UX plus fail-closed checks before permission requests and every native connection\n- preserve streaming, binary responses, models, logs, process views, chat, summaries, and slides through one bounded bridge\n- install/uninstall the macOS and Linux native host with `summarize daemon`; keep Direct and Browser modes daemonless\n- document exact `ExtensionSettings.blocked_permissions`, per-ID `runtime_blocked_hosts`, `NativeMessagingBlocklist`, `NativeMessagingUserLevelHosts`, and managed-storage policies\n\n## Verification\n\n- format, type-aware lint, core/root typechecks: passed\n- Vitest with coverage: 542 files passed, 29 skipped; 2,900 tests passed, 43 skipped; 91.77% statements\n- production Native Messaging Chromium E2E: passed (Chrome extension → native process → daemon health/auth/models/SSE → UI)\n- focused policy/permission/manifest Chromium tests: 12 passed\n- full Chromium UI regression suite: 105 passed, 5 intentionally skipped; one service-worker startup timeout passed immediately in isolation\n- production Chrome zip and Firefox build: passed\n- generated Chrome manifest: `nativeMessaging` only in `optional_permissions`; no `127.0.0.1` host grant or optional host grant\n- production bundle: test-only HTTP transport symbol absent\n\nThe aggregate `pnpm check` rerun was stopped before scripts by the active minimum-release-age policy for unchanged lockfile entry `@earendil-works/pi-ai@0.80.2`. The installed-tree format, lint, typecheck, and full test commands above all passed; no lockfile or dependency-policy change is included.\n\n## Product decisions / limitations\n\n- Windows Daemon mode still needs a packaged native-host `.exe`; the implementation deliberately does not add a weaker command-file workaround. Direct and Browser modes continue to work.\n- Removing required `<all_urls>` is necessary to remove direct loopback capability. Cross-origin plain-HTTP background fetches are therefore no longer guaranteed; restoring that edge case should use an explicit per-origin permission design.\n- `http://localhost/*` remains for Direct Ollama and local-page Browser workflows. Managed deployments that require no local HTTP can block localhost, IPv4 loopback, and IPv6 loopback with the documented exact-ID `runtime_blocked_hosts`; normal cloud Direct and Browser use remains available.\n- The daemon remains a bearer-token HTTP service on loopback behind the native host. Native Messaging removes Chrome extension loopback access, but an unrelated local process that obtains the token can still call the daemon; an OS-authenticated socket would be a separate hardening project.\n",
        "branch": "codex/native-messaging-companion",
